The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the minus against closing.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
The transactions with the shares of <0xC4><0x8C>EZ reached almost half of the normal daily business.
The Prague Stock Exchange started trading at the beginning of Tuesday’s trades on Monday, when it fell another six percentage points.
This time the reason for the burglary was on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which it had refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there.
Fall of shares in Asia
Shares on the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng Stock Exchange index in Hong Kong lost almost four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to offset some of the losses, reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
Taiwan’s stock market fell by 3.6 per cent, according to the index.
"The timing of the rescue in the United States is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," Hong Kong's chief monetary officer Joseph Yam said in a statement.
Hong Kong, although belonging to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries are likely to be affected by the collapse.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
The US House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion CZK) should be spent.
The lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices recorded the biggest plunge in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell nearly seven percent, a similar decline it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was little evidence that the draft would not pass in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress Admits U.S. Government May Pump $700 Billion Into Banks
The top representatives of the American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial aid for the American financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers reached a breakthrough in talks to pass a rescue plan in the form of financial aid to the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner).
However, this is not yet a victory.
Congressional representatives still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to various reports, the plan could probably be voted on in the Senate at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a notification that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of the financial markets.
After that, however, there will be a "disenchantment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could also help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like,” Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to him, a final vote could be held on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsold mortgage assets by financial companies, which plunge financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We have to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we are on target,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also striking in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the words of the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
This is to reassure investors about deals in the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect the deals on Monday.
However, it is not yet entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is uncertainty about whether the negotiations could still fail at the last minute on a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
However, the law will see some changes.
The total amount allocated to aid the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
Congress can, however, block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
Although the president has a veto right in this decision, Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, which was based on obtaining funds for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We have worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, then the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday’s progress and “appreciate the bilateral effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restriction of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, concluding benefits, and a timetable for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies involved in the program and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be led by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard and made great progress toward an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes help for homeowners who are having trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys, with the goal being to lower the monthly cost to the debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
"And that's because you don't know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses among themselves," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or early next week is not decisive in Marek’s view.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and approve it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that there will be an adoption is the most important thing at this moment," Marek said.
Duel on knife's edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can still make phone calls.
So, of course, it looks like it is better to just buy a phone.
After all, there are plenty of reasons why you should hire an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owners.
Surely it is difficult to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
Once such musical innovations do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music on the go, i.e. with compressed music, in simple terms - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will probably hardly be able to afford headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for each.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can play a lot more than just music, but what mobile phones can do, they don’t even create hints.
No modern device is as universal to use as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephony and sims, it can play music and videos, record both, it sometimes has a better, sometimes a worse camera and maybe even navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music for longer than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect cheap phones to be able to play music for no more than a few hours.
If you still call from time to time, you’d better buy a charger for the office for safety – this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones will keep at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with a one-time charge.
Another problem is if you want to overplay the music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB port, and not every phone without special software can be connected directly to a PC.
Of course, you can play the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers are finished without reduction with the tiny memory cards that are used in mobile phones.
For players, you do not need any special software, except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to power the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, arranged by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can be more
When choosing a specific device, you should ask yourself in particular about the battery life, storage capacity, quality and type of sound, and of course also about the ease of use.
If your music is mostly behind the scenes and you only hear it for a short time every day, for example, in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
This is something that almost every cell phone can do.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can process.
MP3 create all, and most of the music you get will be right in that format.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service can be a powerful argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab the phone in the jacket pocket while the player is lying at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost any phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you get a very decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most people will be that no normal headphones are present.
The best and most technically advanced phones with a 3.5mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the player in turn lies in the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the former normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable is obvious.
It does not threaten a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile internet and a subsequently horrifying bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you use now?
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns will suffice.
But beware.
For the basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive ones can also read 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then go to Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more demanding listeners, prefer to take specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The biggest one is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series phones have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours) provide you MP3 players from the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe he won’t be able to wait much longer.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile service providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are the prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fighting fantasy.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile phone providers, on the other hand, like to scoff at the fact that there is an enormous amount of competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, is also often obliged to do so.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way, he would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market that brought about a significant price reduction, which then also the classic mobile providers had to respond to.
Prior to the launch of Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you do not need to look for examples for long.
In February this year, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not require a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually turn out to be low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could take hold in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, mobile phone providers say
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to prevent a potential competitor from emerging.
Your interest in starting a virtual mobile phone provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe there will be better times.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in rare agreement with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
And she adds: “T-Mobile’s network will hardly feature a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer in order to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the suppliers
The approach of the mobile service providers is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was coming from the company T-Mobile when U:fon came on the market.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now, U:fon is a good argument for why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> noted: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile carrier.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is the sole proprietor of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile phone provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not of sufficient interest to the classical providers", Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS said in his response to our request.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
This is more than a concern of an authority that represents the interests of consumers and is intended, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is really shocking in this case is the almost already touching harmony of the three mobile service providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely same price of petrol at the petrol stations is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not detected any evidence in this case that suggests anti-competitive conduct and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so he also does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions in the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile service providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - for its network the monopoly.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
But even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile service providers act remarkably similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The shift of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> failed to enforce the extension of its competences to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS only need to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay if no one's watching
The first thing that remains unnoticed is the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
There are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile carriers prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which can lead to a termination of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not resonate with the managers of the mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, the activities of these companies give them not to be neglected profits, at the same time they - unlike the actual virtual providers - are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all this, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full access to it like the regular customers of the mobile service providers."
That alone, however, should at least seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>TU.
There is also another question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
The mobile phone providers close their eyes before such an approach, why are they locking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences for the detection of such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the providers, they would not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers has brought a significant decrease in the price of the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which in no way tried to safeguard the interests of mobile phone providers, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal printing, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we can not get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But we do not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider is soon to appear, the Czech mobile market may soon set in motion again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminatory) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will not be able to make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
