When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it poses dead, flees or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a similar subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in the execution/control functions).
This wide region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be acquired, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analyzed on the basis of our own experience because of the special hardware, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my explanations relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more accessible scientifically.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the state of visualization.
What happens to the sensations?
I refer them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one’s own brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and especially humans.
Linked to the linguistic nature, fine gradations of the feeling result, because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar, in order to attribute them to others in addition to ourselves.
In contrast, for example, Antonio Damasio suggests that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and the brain stem arise similarly to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in multi-genre sensations.
Theoretically, I can’t argue with that, but I think it’s unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels the same way in both cases, but how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same way if they behave similarly?
Does a scabies flee in danger if it also feels fear?
In my view, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain stem cells, on the other hand, ravens do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to man: how would you prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even raccoons (who knows?), have feelings.
But I didn't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I’d rather explore emotional behavior than the emotional feelings of rats.
In any case, progress on the neural level is indicated here, provided that the same is measured in rats and humans.
As I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor do I explore sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You might think that’s short-sighted, but I’d rather get ahead than run against a wall all the time.
I am a practical emotionalist.
