The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the road was first made public during the session this month.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said the company wanted to use the road but did not necessarily want to own it.
“The main concern of Avalon Bay is to renovate this decayed lane and make it a public meeting place,” she said, adding that the city had proposed the sale itself.
Seth Donlin, spokesman for the Building Protection Department, said it was actually the city’s desire to sell the street and stressed the department’s task was to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its colorful neighborhood, The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historic appeal.
Some believe that the street got its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was divided among his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was claimed by none.
The back door of the CBGB music club, the punk rock memorial, which was closed in 2006, opened to the Extra Place and the street is probably best known as the backdrop for the photo on the cover of the album "Rocket to Russia" by Ramones.
The patch was great, said Danny Fields, the manager of the Ramones, who took the photo in November 1976.
The road was full of debris, lumps and parts of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that this public land, as modest as it is, should continue to be public.
Others have hailed Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged splinter of the city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's Disappearing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Grievances: A Bitter Nostalgic Look at the Dying City"), has published part of the urban history talk about Extra Place, which was published in the magazine "The New Yorker" in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: “Extra Place is a small narrow dead end that remains dark even during the day and is characterized by rusty metal doors of the warehouses, closed windows and weekly newspapers flying past rain gutters.”
With a few exceptions, the street looked just like it did last night.
A rat ran through the back of the street, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where a more expensive clothing store is now located.
Graffiti was visible on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bundle of ransacked newspapers.
Some passers-by said they rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that the road could be polished up a bit.
Fields, added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the appeal of the street in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in places that were dark, damp and disgusting.
Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Fellow in Caliphonic Studies and Director of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choice.”
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s education proposals are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the probability of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students” — which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among others, a bilingual transition phase in education for those who are just learning English.
Nevertheless, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school achievement.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Yet in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth graders passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This amazing success has been achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school practices the approach of training in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly the point Obama should pay attention to, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach places emphasis on the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist instruction.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, said to me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later, you would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him.
“It works,” she noted, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English learners?
The achievements of the school would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s answer uncertain.
While agreeing with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation that targets “English only.”
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider education models that work, rather than disparaging and trivializing them.
Oil prices fall as a result of renewed fears about the economy
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday amid fears that even the U.S. bailout plan for financial markets might not be enough to revive the economy.
Crude oil futures on the New York Stock Exchange fell 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel in the morning session.
Since last Monday, the price has dropped by more than $20.
Over the past two weeks, the commodity markets have been shaken by both the financial turmoil on Wall Street and the powerful turmoil in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices peaked at $145.29 per barrel in July, they fell to almost $90 per barrel this month, then rose again, as a result of the enormous uncertainty in the financial markets.
On Monday, investors again expressed concern, although congressional representatives had announced that they had agreed on a rescue plan over the weekend, which should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the last chapter of the growing crisis, Citigroup is expected to buy up the banking operations of the Wachovia Corporation, according to a government statement on Monday.
Meanwhile, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalised the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it seems that it has failed to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, it is expected that demand for goods, including oil, will continue to decline.
Analysts at Deutsche Bank wrote in a statement to investors that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates had become extremely uncertain.
We believe they continue to write that the commodity markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of commodity markets, we are most concerned about whether the U.S. American virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
The Bank’s analysts have downgraded their oil consumption expectations due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and lowered their forecasts for the oil and gas price for 2009 by 20%.
