Retired Gebrselassie breaks his world record
Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has once again shown why some consider him the best long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to reach the 42.2 km track in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59 Gebrselassie improved his previous score from 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has achieved at least one world championship title or set a world record on every track from one kilometer to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Olympic marathon in Beijing, out of fear that the air pollution might worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - at sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie has won with an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since runners such as Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya switched to long distance, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in 1998 in Berlin with the result 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had had convulsions in his calf two weeks ago and was therefore unable to train for a week.
Obviously, after a break, he was refreshed and not roasted back.
"I'm so happy," he told reporters.
“Everything went perfectly.
I resumed training a week ago and had some concerns today, but in the end everything was great."
He has been criticized – especially in Kenya, Ethiopia’s East African rivals – for over-orchestrating his races, avoiding many of the world’s top marathon stars in general, relying too heavily on race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records over the competition.
But this criticism hardly harms the size Gebrselassies as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the center of the track in 1:02:04.
Two Kenyan elite runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the Tempomachers dropped out.
Just over three miles before the finish, Gebrselassie made his last start to separate from Kwambai, who came second in 2:05:36 and thus improved his best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
For women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, has completed a remarkable year by showing at 2:19:19 the seventh fastest result of all time.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff from the United Kingdom.
Last spring, the 36-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the games in Beijing due to problems described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She skilfully planned her run by having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners tear up first, but overtaken after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya came third in 2:25:01.
The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the outcrops of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet town where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black city in the country and the home town of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three playgrounds, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city that describes it – and that made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida guidebook produced by the Federal Writers’ Project during the Depression – remains a place of very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who “so little knows about us that he doesn’t know what he’s missing.”
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
“We’re very concerned about how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a city resident and parishioner of the city’s oldest church.
It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other, an example of the – sometimes condemned, sometimes praised – black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on the lookout.
And so the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in oral form, such as Mules and Men (1953) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Bold as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Off the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-and-white-painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and what-also-always fits in class rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston thus connected Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
This was definitely not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by citing the men singing songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came into town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable clothing style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” said Mr. Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he swayed in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books ran out.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary of Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no big commemoration, no public readings in the grand style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a 2003 biography of Hurston.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the municipality's slow two-lane highway.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At this time, a bunch of white boys often came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to force integration, calling its decision in Brown’s case against the school board “offensive rather than respectful of my race.”
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group unity in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being hugged — I remember — they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group protecting the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
“You didn’t hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher — I mean there’s a cultural divide,” Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped create space for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors and artists who have set themselves above prejudice, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much praised Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, making it again a part of the American literary canon.
The long-distance project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane long-distance road enlivened the city, accelerated the whole thing with top speed, aroused real citizen pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the long-distance project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
More and more trainees came, as did Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-appreciate the past.
Eatonville was added to the country's historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a specialty in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a backstreet in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is now 90% black.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, a permit is required in advance and certain things – such as the wall painting of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and representing black men at field work – must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Mrs. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their screened community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew, an increased degree of home pride was born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, which he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to properly describe Eatonville.
“Most people who only go through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after church.
“But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
Here in New York, we speak financial Latin fluently.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stands and the huge television screens in Times Square, they would not even realize that they are in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that over their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, daily have the worst horror work day since the stock market crash of 1929.
The suppliers still push the metal tea trolleys along sidewalks with loud claps and carry trays loaded with muffins for breakfast sessions.
Latinos still wander between apartments, like human pack animals loaded with the 50 ironed T-shirts hanging on a yoke-like pole on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bagel on the sidewalks and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn’t feel like a crisis at all until I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon due to all the global recession.
Although I had decided to place my compulsory course on time on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase branch, about 20 people were already queued.
Not at the money counters to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for directions to Macy's department store, and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, I learned later from Starr, my “personal bank employee with license,” stood for the same reason I stood snake.
