They had raised money from so-called Thriftys (a bit like a construction bank), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state and say they treat their customers like family.
In the past year, 15 of these banks have gone silently and quietly bankrupt.
In the past few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into bankruptcy management over and as last Friday New Yorkers drove home over the weekend, was Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion in savings assets, looking for a saver.
In fear of another crash, the office and store employees in front of me brought their bar to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank that is responsible for most rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Quite normal New Yorkers have acquired flowing financial latin in recent weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese tribal supermarket took reference to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and their disembodied CEO Dick Fuld with so much familiarity, as if she were slandering a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge at my block of flat, got away from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
