Muslim graves desecrated during right-wing skirmish in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-wing leader of Austria's right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, a member of Belgium's right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, took part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008, to represent the "Cities Against Islamization" organization.
They carry signs in the style of traffic signs on which a mosque is depicted, crossed with a red line.
The police accused right-wing extremists of the grave breach in a Muslim cemetery in Austria, on the same weekend at which extreme right-wing parties recorded significant gains in the country’s parliamentary elections.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves in the cemetery in Traun near Linz were badly damaged in an organized action, according to police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols like the David Star on some of the graves, but criminal officials consider this an attempt to disguise the motive of the extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the burial, which took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan is coming to an end.
At the same time, a round of conscience research is underway in Austria after the country slipped to the right in yesterday’s parliamentary election.
The FP<0xC3><0x96> and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that received almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law and some of their electoral slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
