Interview - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public trust, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, during the 1980s, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donor Service were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and at developing guidelines to prevent a re-catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever still hesitated to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee at the time, whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood canned food in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to reports from Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec took up their work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservation system in Quebec,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through work in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly emphasizing that by early 2008, almost 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary is aware that <0x60>trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which you apply exclusionary measures if you do not know this and if a disease is only slowly progressing, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which results from a degeneration of the brain, which is inevitable.
So no blood was taken in April 1999 from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was without any doubt proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow to directly detect the presence of the virus in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and this could not be recognized, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone would be infected with HIV.
Because Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmission via a blood canister to occur.
I believe that you can feel comfortable with this nowadays if you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says the head of the board of directors of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We have to monitor continuously," continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate care in addition to a safe supply.
“The demand is rising because the population is getting older.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also affects the blood donation network, which on average only accounts for 3% of Quebec’s eligible residents.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they have AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent are excluded from blood donation for one year.
<0x60>With this 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to keep it and get it to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood canned but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being interspersed with Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, there is abundant blood in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,” continues Dr. Décary, who describes this umbilical cord blood loss program as very popular.
"Many mothers are convinced they don't have access to it," because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
