Free will - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms and follows an Orwellian logic that the world’s largest gold-mining company sought a libel lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small, unfunded publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they are not judging the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposing opinions.
No matter how the process goes, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
Incidentally, the tactic in these unequal battles is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual arrangement that makes the opposite side mouth off and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to the public.
Contrary to what is going and going in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas and not through knuckle-dragging.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent testing teams that could have brought light to this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes out the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a handshake.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can ask for a ‘public’ debate at the same time, while ignoring the opinions of this public?
Apparently, in the vice president’s world, this word includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a pretty narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public supporting the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the gold mine’s brutal stance.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as grumbling (in the course of the <0x60>public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a claim to the authors of Noir Canada, in which they refer to them).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss the facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of the world do not like, who else can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to get hold of debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures that limit this kind of unjustified lawsuits.
Wall Street Rescue: Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and leading congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be adopted by the two chambers of Congress.
The main contents are: better control of the deputies over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new provisions to limit the number of houses held due to payment arrears, as well as the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Senator Judd Gregg, who attended the negotiations, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
“Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: If we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, out of fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on investors’ mood.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who were only late in the negotiations, showed themselves to be more in favor of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama insisted on the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, especially those that would allow the owners to keep their homes, and those that would affect the salaries of the executives of the state-saved companies.
“When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is not something to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, “I’d like to know the details first, but I hope so.
<0x60>The guidelines I have read [show] that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan is geared toward using taxpayers’ money
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before expanding to other forms of extended bond (PCAA), and finally led to a freeze of financial power and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt at consensus last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of distressed societies should only be secured by the government and not bought, it is believed to escape the dead end.
To round out the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then raise new taxes to recover the capital it has invested.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion must be approved by a re-vote of Congress.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the aided companies, which pay him dividends in the event of winnings, and which it can resell once the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to suspend the seizure proceedings in respect of the dwellings linked to the real estate loans affected by this plan, and also to set deadlines for repayment and severance payments to the senior employees of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on it today, and then the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get a green light.
In fact, yesterday there were more votes against this project, both from the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his voters.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of asking the taxpayers to checkout.'
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, leader of a group in Congress called “the caucus of skeptics,” presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to inform us: We ask Congress not to be pressured and to carefully consider which way to go,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, we again got the proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which is in great difficulty since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) in the crisis due to the risky real estate loans.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and the 10 largest insurers.
“This is not lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
To compensate, we receive a right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are looming.”
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was just about to nationalize another bank that had been put in jeopardy by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, including over 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) from real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy up the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
According to Northern Rock, Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank that the British government has had to nationalise since the beginning of this financial crisis.
