The Psychology of Overselling – or Why We’re Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate what is offered.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore ready to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play lotto, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which overcoming the opponent plays a significant role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group also conducted research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerge as the winner of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis in one group was on winning, while in the other group it was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group playing "against loss" were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or "profit" group.
"These results cannot be inferred from any previous economic theory.
This is because they have so far only justified the behaviour observed in auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we have now prepared a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor to visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at hundreds of thousands in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, secretion or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to get a vaccine against the A and B viruses anyway, there is no vaccine against the C virus.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and the recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the much more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoo artists.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the GP at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, which eliminates the risk of infection and prevents the formation of cancer.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
