Intelligent car imitates the flight of the hummus
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummeln to create new accident avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the autorobot-controlled biomimetic system BR23C, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval “private area,” which is very similar to our own “shield,” Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The bee’s compound eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the autorobot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the autorobot wouldn’t be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autorobot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer that is currently considered unavoidable within accidents.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, unlike the bees, the deflection can not be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking, of the autorobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process some inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not have to store them, or use previous maneuvers to produce an intuitive, logical response, so that it continuously requires only a handful of KB of memory.
It does not require any gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously guiding the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
