The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon had already revealed itself a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House’s $700 billion savings package: A large portion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s edition of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis is gradually tearing apart the Republican Party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to “those in Washington” and the financial world in the south.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example just mentioned, however, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond, will be affected by these.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-awaited events that, under these new conditions, are finally taking shape and coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the wealth of private households living in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for the governments: namely, how to behave towards the affected families, who are also a huge mass of voters.
So the crisis appears to be global in economic terms, but it is almost purely national in political terms.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen into disrepute and lost its right to speak: the obvious evidence for this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially distribution of relief funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the United States is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two not-to-be-overvalued conditions – under certain circumstances – that no other international organization and no market will be able to use in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been attached to a sector most closely related to the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, just now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked realm, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we must at once see how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is preferable to another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short push in.
He who says territory, he who says government, he who says politics, he also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a profound and, in a sense, still disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, all aimed at a whole class of managers of the Western countries.
