The super glue that lets go up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centers, one of which has now seemingly almost reached its goal.
Using an adhesive applied to an area of only 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers were able to fix a 100 kg body to a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the already used adhesives, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of adhesive can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged to a stack of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered with microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time "makes it easy to remove from the wall," said Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall within the field of space travel.
For now, the superheroes will have to wait.
THE OTHER ART OF RESEARCH – also the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that, like hair, clean themselves from the dust by moving on a surface, thus always maintaining a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and their vitamin richness especially in the summer, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital drugs, since they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices associated with medication intake. As part of the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: it is enough to drink a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice so that patients will be able to consume it.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago about the dangers of this mix, and emphasizes paying attention to what is drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepam or methadone.
IT’S NOT JUST GRAPEFRUIT – According to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Therefore, the appeal of Michele Carruba, the director of the Universit<0xC3><0xA0> Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still uncertainties, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
Nobel Prize goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize goes to Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
