Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has arrived; as a free replacement for Microsoft’s Office, the Open Source software is gaining an ever-increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now spartan designed start menu, is finally a fundamentally guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x version, as well as the support for the new format 1.
Attention was also paid to the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which, for example, facilitates sending via email. This also includes the ability to import PDF files into graphic editing modules while preserving the original appearance of the page.
Thus, it is now also possible to generate "hybrid" PDF files, which expand the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of applications: tables can now be edited multiple-handedly by different users, avoiding conflicts with changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a frank to ensure a better correction process.
Some companies are just about to publish various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while in the coming weeks the final result is expected to be made public.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. It follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to your home or office.
However, freedom of the press can be an incentive for the dissemination of the program in private households, so it is precisely in the area of business, where OpenOffice could succeed the great throw: after all, various public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means an optimal help for small and medium-sized companies, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims at a displacement of Excel; Impress, to create presentations as with Powerpoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more well-known access; and lastly, Draw, a graphic module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
