Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long term the death of the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
Mostly historical places full of memories are affected, "it's like losing a friend, with whom you have traveled a piece of street full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which is lost forever in kinow.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the huge amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this brand paid for the most part the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 it is both in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also arise, but first of all the preservation of the already existing, because closing a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are ready to look for a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the missing state for the fund of the trade association remains outside attention: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed.
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears surrounding the old cinemas, has decided to protect them through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting the traditional cinemas, both in the historical center and in the peripheries.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax incentives for cinema operators as well as advantages for the public in relation to local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at a cheaper parking fee.
“It’s a pleasant initiative,” said Giuseppe Tornatore, “I hope that other cities will join our example and also come up with new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to align something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because after all, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dusty posters.
