When the energy springs from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up
It is a non-delaying source of money, covering over 70% of the planet’s surface, and only now do the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not by chance these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was lost, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by the energies generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also the currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, which in 2005 signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now focusing on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and considering the possibility of working with us.”
This is about obtaining an approval from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being promoted by the US in Alaska, and President Bush only recently initiated plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Yet more improved technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by environmentalists.
So far, projects like the one in Portugal and Scotland are rather small in size and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, it requires technologies with a far greater impact on the environment.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via subsea lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for the state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Generation Research, a particular interest immediately deserves the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, the solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to $35 million is already planned for 2009.
